    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MuTA72">
<l>kuṉṟoṉṟi ṉāya kuṟamakaḷir kōlvaḷaikkai</l>
<l>ceṉṟu viḷaiyāṭun tīṅkaḻaipōy – veṉṟu</l>
<l>viḷaṅkumati kōḷviṭukkum vēṅkaṭamē mēlai</l>
<l>yiḷaṅkumarar kōmā ṉiṭam</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Vēṅkaṭam,<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">For this earlier type of inset clause typical of Caṅkam literature cf. note on Po. 38, with further parallels in Po. 40, Pū. 53, 75, Pē. 45, 58, 68, 71, 75 and 89.</note></l>
<l>where the hill women who are on the sole hill, go [their] hands with pretty</l>
<l>bangles moving<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">The position of the absolutive ceṉṟu is slightly awkward, since syntax suggests to read the preceding kai as its direct object. It seems better to accept a subject-change and take kai as subject, which leaves us with a semantic embarassment since cel-tal, “to go”, is not usually employed for the action of hands.</note>, to the playing sweet bamboo [flute and] victoriously</l>
<l>make the planet<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">kōḷ is the Tamil calque of Sanskrit graha, “planet“, and is here used to refer to Rahu, the cosmic snake that periodically swallows the moon and has to be induced to set it free again.</note> set the shining moon free</l>
<l>is the place of the king of young princes<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">According to Tarkkatīrttar Rāmānujācāryar, this means the nityasūri, who are forever young.</note> above<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here mēlai can be taken in a spatial or also in a temporal sense as “earlier”.</note>.</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
</text>
